43
00:02:29.600 --> 00:02:33.040
So the target that we've been interested in for

44
00:02:33.600 --> 00:02:37.420
over a decade now, sorry, should I say two decades now, is

45
00:02:37.460 --> 00:02:41.300
the integrin alpha V beta 6. You may have heard a

46
00:02:41.340 --> 00:02:45.060
little bit about it. It's an epithelial-specific cell surface

47
00:02:45.120 --> 00:02:45.640
receptor.

48
00:02:46.440 --> 00:02:50.360
It's undetectable on most healthy adult tissue, but

49
00:02:50.420 --> 00:02:54.320
it's highly upregulated in many cancers, including some of the most

50
00:02:54.400 --> 00:02:57.040
lethal malignancies such as pancreatic cancer.

51
00:02:57.780 --> 00:03:01.500
It plays a key role in invasion and metastasis, and unfortunately, its

52
00:03:01.510 --> 00:03:05.000
presence on tumors is a negative prognostic indicator for the

53
00:03:05.060 --> 00:03:08.890
patient. So we and others, we're not the only people working on this

54
00:03:08.920 --> 00:03:12.470
target, believe that the high contrast between malignant and

55
00:03:12.540 --> 00:03:16.440
healthy tissue and the functional relevance of beta 6 makes a

56
00:03:16.500 --> 00:03:19.970
good target for the development of both diagnostics and

57
00:03:20.060 --> 00:03:23.020
therapeutics, i.e. radioligand therapies.

58
00:03:25.200 --> 00:03:28.310
So our efforts started, and we spent a lot of

59
00:03:28.440 --> 00:03:31.700
time in the diagnostic space. So when

60
00:03:31.740 --> 00:03:35.220
we started to look at the integrin alpha V beta 6,

61
00:03:35.960 --> 00:03:39.840
nothing was known about the target. There wasn't a crystal structure.

62
00:03:40.440 --> 00:03:43.400
So we went to the literature, and what we were finding was a lot of

63
00:03:43.440 --> 00:03:47.000
publications with regards to the role of alpha V beta

64
00:03:47.420 --> 00:03:50.000
6 in the foot-and-mouth disease virus.

65
00:03:50.400 --> 00:03:53.580
Well, the foot-and-mouth disease virus is a virus that cattle get.

66
00:03:54.060 --> 00:03:57.780
So you're probably wondering, well, what's that got to do with developing a

67
00:03:57.820 --> 00:03:59.900
cancer diagnostic or a therapeutic?

68
00:04:00.430 --> 00:04:04.300
Well, it turned out that the virus got into

69
00:04:04.340 --> 00:04:08.180
its host cell via the integrin alpha V beta 6,

70
00:04:08.560 --> 00:04:11.760
and the crystal structure of the virus was known.

71
00:04:12.720 --> 00:04:16.421
It turned out that a 20 amino acid peptide on the

72
00:04:16.459 --> 00:04:19.940
GH loop of viral protein one was responsible for

73
00:04:20.019 --> 00:04:22.909
shuffling the virus into its host cell.

74
00:04:23.520 --> 00:04:27.440
So long story short, and 10 years of work, we took

75
00:04:27.480 --> 00:04:31.020
that 20 amino acid peptide. So you'll see

76
00:04:31.080 --> 00:04:34.740
A20FMDV2, so from the foot-and-mouth disease virus.

77
00:04:35.040 --> 00:04:38.040
It's called two because it had a lysine mutated out of it.

78
00:04:38.540 --> 00:04:42.260
And we spent a decade tweaking it. At that point, I have

79
00:04:42.280 --> 00:04:46.140
a lab full of chemists, so all they wanted to do was tweak with the structure to

80
00:04:46.180 --> 00:04:49.600
improve its stability, come up with cool ways to radiolabel it

81
00:04:49.660 --> 00:04:53.440
with fluorine for PET, because we did a lot of F-18 PET work

82
00:04:53.480 --> 00:04:57.020
then. Before we came up with this agent that we're now

83
00:04:57.100 --> 00:05:00.250
calling F-18 alpha V beta 6 binding

84
00:05:00.360 --> 00:05:04.150
peptide. So I just highlight the amount of effort that went into just

85
00:05:04.560 --> 00:05:08.540
developing the first F-18 radiolabeled peptide

86
00:05:08.720 --> 00:05:12.660
for diagnostic with PET. A lot of preclinical testing, a lot of in vitro

87
00:05:12.760 --> 00:05:16.140
testing, in vivo testing in many different mouse models.

88
00:05:17.460 --> 00:05:21.160
Multiple iterations on this compound to get it stable, to get it

89
00:05:21.240 --> 00:05:24.300
targeted. So after that 10 years of work,

90
00:05:25.940 --> 00:05:29.820
we applied for our first IND with the FDA, and

91
00:05:29.860 --> 00:05:33.720
we opened a clinical trial in patients with breast, colon,

92
00:05:34.020 --> 00:05:37.700
lung, and pancreas cancer. So what you're seeing here, and

93
00:05:37.760 --> 00:05:40.440
hopefully it's pointing, yeah. On the left here,

94
00:05:41.260 --> 00:05:44.280
is a patient with metastatic lung cancer.

95
00:05:44.720 --> 00:05:48.140
This is a maximum intensity projection image through the

96
00:05:48.200 --> 00:05:51.960
patient one hour after the injection with our F-18 peptide.

97
00:05:52.440 --> 00:05:56.190
And you can see here uptake in the lung, but also in

98
00:05:56.260 --> 00:06:00.040
these bone lesions. Now, this is clear through the kidneys, so these

99
00:06:00.060 --> 00:06:04.020
dark spots here are kidneys. We do see a little bit of activity in the

100
00:06:04.140 --> 00:06:07.860
stomach and the GI tract, but this is an F-18

101
00:06:07.940 --> 00:06:10.800
image taken one hour after injection of the

102
00:06:10.820 --> 00:06:14.804
peptideHere you see another patient,

103
00:06:15.014 --> 00:06:18.104
metastatic breast cancer. So you see the primary.

104
00:06:18.144 --> 00:06:21.604
We're seeing lymph nodes. We're also seeing bone metastasis.

105
00:06:21.624 --> 00:06:25.264
This patient has a lot more GI activity than this patient.

106
00:06:25.324 --> 00:06:28.464
We're seeing quite a bit of variability from patient to patient.

107
00:06:29.984 --> 00:06:30.864
Now, one

108
00:06:31.724 --> 00:06:35.684
image that was shocking to us was when we took this agent

109
00:06:35.724 --> 00:06:39.584
into non-small cell lung cancer with patients with brain mets,

110
00:06:40.164 --> 00:06:43.124
and we saw here what you're seeing is a slice through the brain.

111
00:06:43.864 --> 00:06:46.064
This is uptake of our compound in the brain.

112
00:06:46.644 --> 00:06:50.224
And what you're also seeing is healthy brain doesn't have any

113
00:06:50.284 --> 00:06:53.664
compound. So we're seeing this exquisite resolution here.

114
00:06:53.984 --> 00:06:57.964
That lesion in the brain was three millimeters, and for those of you in the

115
00:06:58.024 --> 00:07:00.804
PET world, that's below the resolution of the scanner.

116
00:07:01.224 --> 00:07:04.804
But taking into account the super high affinity of our agent with the

117
00:07:04.864 --> 00:07:08.464
clearance in the background, we were seeing these super tiny lesions.

118
00:07:11.064 --> 00:07:13.784
So I pause here, and you look at the timeline.

119
00:07:14.124 --> 00:07:18.104
The first peptide we developed was probably in about 2004.

120
00:07:18.684 --> 00:07:21.304
We are now at 2017,

121
00:07:22.164 --> 00:07:25.864
and we are still only seeing. And of course, we're

122
00:07:25.944 --> 00:07:29.344
seeing a lot more, but we're just detecting at this point.

123
00:07:30.034 --> 00:07:31.774
And so what you're looking at here,

124
00:07:33.144 --> 00:07:36.884
the image on the-- This is a patient that came to clinic with a

125
00:07:37.104 --> 00:07:39.784
suspect recurrence of breast cancer

126
00:07:40.604 --> 00:07:44.344
following bilateral mastectomy, following multiple rounds of

127
00:07:44.424 --> 00:07:48.124
chemotherapy and suspect recurrence in the lymph node.

128
00:07:48.704 --> 00:07:50.984
That's what she thought walking into the clinic.

129
00:07:52.324 --> 00:07:55.904
Insurance declined her FDG-PET, so she entered into our

130
00:07:55.944 --> 00:07:59.894
clinical trial, and this is what we saw one hour after

131
00:07:59.944 --> 00:08:03.804
injection of our F-18 peptide. So yes, there's

132
00:08:03.864 --> 00:08:07.344
uptake in that lesion, as expected, but we

133
00:08:07.444 --> 00:08:11.404
saw all this bone uptake. Now, my first

134
00:08:11.464 --> 00:08:14.614
reaction as a chemist was, did the fluoride fall off the molecule?

135
00:08:15.184 --> 00:08:18.094
But remember, this molecule had been into 20 patients prior.

136
00:08:18.284 --> 00:08:21.953
It's very stable. So we looked towards the CT scan of this

137
00:08:21.984 --> 00:08:25.464
patient, and these lesions were real. These were bone mets.

138
00:08:26.064 --> 00:08:28.584
So went back to the referring oncologist,

139
00:08:29.564 --> 00:08:32.184
who called the insurance, and they got the FDG-PET.

140
00:08:33.064 --> 00:08:35.384
Turn my phone off here. Got the FDG-PET.

141
00:08:35.975 --> 00:08:39.884
And you're seeing is this is the same patient a week apart.

142
00:08:39.924 --> 00:08:43.784
No treatment in between. The FDG-PET actually didn't

143
00:08:43.845 --> 00:08:46.164
show all of those lesions, though it showed some of them.

144
00:08:47.004 --> 00:08:50.584
So the message here, though, this was really a tipping point for my lab

145
00:08:50.924 --> 00:08:54.484
because yes, FDG-PET saw five

146
00:08:54.544 --> 00:08:56.444
lesions. We saw several hundred.

147
00:08:57.364 --> 00:09:00.464
But the patient already knew they had metastatic breast cancer.

148
00:09:00.504 --> 00:09:03.604
This didn't help them. We saw more, but so what?

149
00:09:03.644 --> 00:09:07.073
So for us it was a tipping point is what can we do with this

150
00:09:07.124 --> 00:09:09.864
information to actually help a patient?

151
00:09:10.524 --> 00:09:12.824
How can we make this into a therapeutic?

152
00:09:13.244 --> 00:09:15.964
Well, what we're all here for today is radioligand therapy.

153
00:09:16.004 --> 00:09:19.284
We can do this using a radiotheranostic approach.

154
00:09:20.944 --> 00:09:24.564
So we went back to the bench because, as most of you know,

155
00:09:24.644 --> 00:09:28.454
fluorine-18 does not have its therapeutic radionuclide counterpart,

156
00:09:28.884 --> 00:09:30.504
and we had to re-engineer the molecule.

157
00:09:30.984 --> 00:09:34.944
I'll be honest, we re-engineered it also from an intellectual property standpoint

158
00:09:35.004 --> 00:09:38.884
because we're now going into a therapeutic. IP is very important.

159
00:09:39.744 --> 00:09:41.404
So we re-engineered the peptide.

160
00:09:42.944 --> 00:09:44.164
We're calling it five-G.

161
00:09:45.884 --> 00:09:49.344
We put a DOTA chelator on there, so you could radiolabel with

162
00:09:49.384 --> 00:09:53.304
gallium-68 for PET imaging. We also put

163
00:09:53.364 --> 00:09:57.184
an albumin binding moiety on there for the therapeutic, so we could increase the

164
00:09:57.364 --> 00:10:01.324
blood circulation time for, and then again, same DOTA chelator

165
00:10:01.504 --> 00:10:03.284
for chelating lutetium.

166
00:10:04.344 --> 00:10:07.604
But we went back to the bench where I told you, what have we done?

167
00:10:07.684 --> 00:10:11.024
We spent 10 years developing the diagnostic.

168
00:10:11.084 --> 00:10:14.844
We went back to the bench, and we had to do all the same in vitro assays, all

169
00:10:14.884 --> 00:10:18.764
the preclinical work. And I want to highlight here,

170
00:10:19.564 --> 00:10:23.144
this group, the Lustgarten Foundation and Stand Up to Cancer,

171
00:10:23.474 --> 00:10:27.184
and some of you are here today from those foundations.

172
00:10:27.224 --> 00:10:30.263
We could not have done this without their support.

173
00:10:30.344 --> 00:10:34.323
In 2018, they put out a grand challenge to

174
00:10:34.404 --> 00:10:37.364
take a compound from bench to bedside in one year,

175
00:10:38.244 --> 00:10:40.384
and they gave us a million dollars to do that.

176
00:10:40.864 --> 00:10:44.604
So that's exactly what we did. We did all this work in one

177
00:10:44.684 --> 00:10:48.624
year. We ended up with two compounds, the gallium agent

178
00:10:48.684 --> 00:10:52.354
for the diagnostic, the lutetium agent for the therapeutic.

179
00:10:53.044 --> 00:10:56.574
Both of them with nanomolar affinity for the target alpha E beta

180
00:10:56.664 --> 00:11:00.594
six. Both of them have high serum stability, so properties that are

181
00:11:00.594 --> 00:11:04.144
very important when you're developing radioligand therapies.

182
00:11:04.184 --> 00:11:08.144
Both of them bound selectively to alpha E beta six and were

183
00:11:08.184 --> 00:11:12.034
rapidly internalized. So this becomes important now as we're delivering

184
00:11:12.034 --> 00:11:15.864
this therapeutic payload. Our molecule is internalized.

185
00:11:16.364 --> 00:11:20.184
Both molecules had good tumor uptake and

186
00:11:20.204 --> 00:11:24.104
tumor retention. And the lutetium preclinically showed

187
00:11:24.164 --> 00:11:25.644
good therapeutic efficacy.

188
00:11:26.804 --> 00:11:30.764
So in October 2020, so yes, all this was done during COVID as

189
00:11:30.804 --> 00:11:34.464
well. I should highlight that. We filed our second

190
00:11:34.564 --> 00:11:37.924
IND to the FDA. And this time for the

191
00:11:38.004 --> 00:11:41.824
theranostic pair. So just for your

192
00:11:41.884 --> 00:11:45.704
information, this was a single IND application that covered both molecules.

193
00:11:46.194 --> 00:11:49.684
And I've already told you, these are very, very different molecules.

194
00:11:49.744 --> 00:11:53.264
So we got our IND approved, went through within, I think it was

195
00:11:53.464 --> 00:11:55.904
29 days. We were very, very happy with that.

196
00:11:56.924 --> 00:11:59.704
And then we moved on to opening our clinical trial.

197
00:12:00.344 --> 00:12:04.254
Again, with support from the Lustgarten Foundation and Stand Up to Cancer,

198
00:12:04.644 --> 00:12:06.384
who funded the clinical trial.

199
00:12:07.224 --> 00:12:09.224
So this is a first-in-human study,

200
00:12:10.204 --> 00:12:13.584
evaluating the safety and efficacy of the gallium and

201
00:12:13.644 --> 00:12:14.204
lutetium

202
00:12:15.004 --> 00:12:18.784
pair in patients with locally advanced or metastatic

203
00:12:18.844 --> 00:12:22.232
pancreatic cancer.Now, the goals of the trial,

204
00:12:22.752 --> 00:12:26.452
number one, can the gallium detect lesions in patients with

205
00:12:26.472 --> 00:12:27.372
advanced disease?

206
00:12:28.192 --> 00:12:30.932
Are the molecules safe? Are they well-tolerated?

207
00:12:31.432 --> 00:12:35.412
And what's going to be the maximum dose of our lutetium agent?

208
00:12:35.472 --> 00:12:36.532
So these were our goals,

209
00:12:38.712 --> 00:12:42.632
and here's our study protocol. Standard eligibility,

210
00:12:43.872 --> 00:12:46.552
patients must have progressed on previous lines of chemo.

211
00:12:46.612 --> 00:12:48.732
Obviously, this is not first line today.

212
00:12:50.252 --> 00:12:52.312
Washout from chemo, two weeks.

213
00:12:53.492 --> 00:12:55.992
The lab parameters that obviously, as you're aware, we're

214
00:12:56.672 --> 00:13:00.652
keeping an eye on is, as you saw, our

215
00:13:00.672 --> 00:13:04.212
agent goes out through the kidneys, so we think the kidneys are going to be our

216
00:13:04.252 --> 00:13:08.092
dose-limiting organ, so we're monitoring creatinine and eGFR

217
00:13:08.132 --> 00:13:08.952
throughout the study.

218
00:13:09.932 --> 00:13:13.212
So patients who meet eligibility come in for a gallium scan.

219
00:13:13.752 --> 00:13:17.462
They have a five milli-- and again, this is all first in human with these agents,

220
00:13:17.481 --> 00:13:19.772
so there's a lot of safety monitoring going on throughout.

221
00:13:21.212 --> 00:13:25.092
They come in, they have a five millicurie injection of the gallium, and we

222
00:13:25.172 --> 00:13:28.752
image them, so we're getting some pharmacokinetic information on this if we wanted

223
00:13:28.792 --> 00:13:32.782
to use it as a standalone diagnostic, and we image them one hour, two hours

224
00:13:32.892 --> 00:13:36.572
post-injection, a lot of lab work on the way, EKGs and vitals

225
00:13:36.612 --> 00:13:37.532
monitored throughout.

226
00:13:38.352 --> 00:13:40.652
And then from the image analysis,

227
00:13:41.572 --> 00:13:44.732
we're looking at an SUV of two times normal.

228
00:13:44.872 --> 00:13:48.212
So if they have lung mets, it's two times normal background in the lung.

229
00:13:48.252 --> 00:13:51.452
If they have liver mets, two times normal activity in the liver.

230
00:13:51.932 --> 00:13:55.071
If they have that, they're then eligible for the treatment.

231
00:13:55.332 --> 00:13:59.052
So they've come down to this part where they're enrolled into the therapy arm.

232
00:14:00.992 --> 00:14:03.832
We designed this protocol around Lutetium.

233
00:14:03.892 --> 00:14:07.412
We didn't want any surprises from the FDA, so it's a 3+3 dose

234
00:14:07.492 --> 00:14:11.232
escalation study. We started with 25 millicuries with a

235
00:14:11.292 --> 00:14:15.032
goal to get to the 200 millicurie based on what's currently in the

236
00:14:15.092 --> 00:14:15.492
clinic.

237
00:14:16.592 --> 00:14:19.232
Whether we need it or not, we give the amino acids.

238
00:14:20.352 --> 00:14:23.372
We didn't use amino acids in our preclinical work, but we were

239
00:14:24.172 --> 00:14:25.872
